1
00:02:26,760 --> 00:02:31,424
It's hard to believe I was a kid here.

2
00:02:31,465 --> 00:02:34,866
This town looks a lot different.

3
00:02:34,901 --> 00:02:37,631
How did it get this way?

4
00:02:37,671 --> 00:02:39,400
I don't know,

5
00:02:39,439 --> 00:02:42,636
but it turns my stomach
to look at this place.

6
00:02:46,146 --> 00:02:49,775
It's painful to remember,

7
00:02:49,816 --> 00:02:54,776
but maybe that's why I need
to walk these streets one last time.

8
00:02:58,892 --> 00:03:02,328
The story of the summer
I unwillingly grew up...

9
00:03:03,563 --> 00:03:07,158
Philip! Hey, Philip!

10
00:03:07,200 --> 00:03:11,159
The summer I learned to hate...

11
00:03:11,204 --> 00:03:14,537
- What's wrong?
- Who's that?

12
00:03:17,077 --> 00:03:19,807
A summer set in motion by one man.

13
00:03:27,320 --> 00:03:29,015
Hey, Philip, you don't know him.

14
00:04:27,414 --> 00:04:29,780
Oh, I'm sorry. Did you want a drag?

15
00:04:34,788 --> 00:04:38,849
My name is Eli Cottonmouth.

16
00:04:40,760 --> 00:04:44,491
You folks sure have
a beautiful little town here.

17
00:04:46,433 --> 00:04:48,924
I'd like to show you something
if you'd let me.

18
00:04:48,969 --> 00:04:50,596
This way.

19
00:04:50,637 --> 00:04:53,834
"Beautiful little town. "

20
00:04:55,075 --> 00:04:56,770
This Eli Cottonmouth,

21
00:04:56,810 --> 00:04:59,404
he was one of those
snake-oil salesmen.

22
00:04:59,446 --> 00:05:01,505
He was the Music Man.

23
00:05:01,548 --> 00:05:02,879
Whoa.

24
00:05:02,916 --> 00:05:04,941
But it wasn't "76 Trombones"

25
00:05:04,985 --> 00:05:07,749
or a cure-all ointment that day.

26
00:05:07,787 --> 00:05:11,382
Eli's specialty was model building.

27
00:05:13,493 --> 00:05:17,054
I can't possibly tell you
the way this single model

28
00:05:17,097 --> 00:05:19,759
captured everyone's imaginations

29
00:05:19,799 --> 00:05:23,462
in a way that was almost magic.

30
00:05:23,503 --> 00:05:26,768
Eli Cottonmouth was dangerous

31
00:05:26,806 --> 00:05:30,970
because he was a man who could
show you places you've never been.

32
00:05:31,011 --> 00:05:35,414
As we all wandered
around this tiny carnival,

33
00:05:35,448 --> 00:05:38,713
Eli kept silent.

34
00:05:38,752 --> 00:05:42,210
He let everyone who wanted to
have their fair share of look-see.

35
00:05:52,866 --> 00:05:55,858
Then taking his cue, he simply said:

36
00:05:55,902 --> 00:05:59,861
You folks sure have
a beautiful little town here.

37
00:06:02,809 --> 00:06:04,800
May I have a show of hands, please?

38
00:06:06,946 --> 00:06:07,935
Unanimous.

39
00:06:07,981 --> 00:06:11,212
And so it came to pass
that Eli Cottonmouth

40
00:06:11,251 --> 00:06:13,412
was going to stay around
for a while,

41
00:06:13,453 --> 00:06:16,479
and the town was
going to have a new centerpiece

42
00:06:16,523 --> 00:06:21,483
for the town's highly-anticipated
bisesquicentennial celebration.

43
00:06:21,528 --> 00:06:26,056
That's 250 years in a tiny model,

44
00:06:26,099 --> 00:06:28,863
a model I've never even seen.

45
00:06:29,903 --> 00:06:33,430
Up until then, the only thing
I ever lost sleep over

46
00:06:33,473 --> 00:06:35,498
were childish daydreams

47
00:06:35,542 --> 00:06:38,807
and the Two-Legged Alligator Man.

48
00:06:38,845 --> 00:06:41,712
This summer
was gonna be different.

49
00:06:54,794 --> 00:06:56,284
Foul ball!

50
00:07:17,317 --> 00:07:20,218
- Hey.
- You did such a good job.

51
00:07:27,694 --> 00:07:32,529
Dude, if you turn around right now,
you can see Camille.

52
00:07:32,565 --> 00:07:35,363
- That's my babysitter.
- But you like her.

53
00:07:35,401 --> 00:07:39,804
- She likes your brother.
- Brock? Nah.

54
00:07:39,839 --> 00:07:43,639
She's looking
at him right now.

55
00:07:43,676 --> 00:07:45,974
- Nah.
- What's up, fellas?

56
00:07:46,012 --> 00:07:48,139
- Hey, Pastor Salem.
- How's it going?

57
00:07:48,181 --> 00:07:50,581
- Good.
- All right, man. Great game.

58
00:07:50,617 --> 00:07:52,949
- Thank you.
- Talk to you soon. See all you guys.

59
00:07:52,986 --> 00:07:54,419
- You guys ready to scoot?
- Yep.

60
00:08:01,895 --> 00:08:04,728
Well, howdy, boys.
How was the game?

61
00:08:04,764 --> 00:08:06,664
Good. We won.

62
00:08:06,699 --> 00:08:08,792
Brock said he'd buy us
milkshakes if we did.

63
00:08:08,835 --> 00:08:10,029
Oh!

64
00:08:10,069 --> 00:08:13,937
No, I said I'd buy the milkshakes
if we lost, but whatever.

65
00:08:13,973 --> 00:08:15,873
Well, that's real nice of you, Brock.

66
00:08:15,909 --> 00:08:17,342
So what'll you have?

67
00:08:17,377 --> 00:08:20,312
I'll have a double chocolate
with plenty of whipped cream, please.

68
00:08:20,346 --> 00:08:23,315
I'll have double vanilla,
plenty of strawberry syrup.

69
00:08:23,349 --> 00:08:25,510
Smart move.

70
00:08:25,552 --> 00:08:28,646
Go ahead, get whatever
you want, man. My treat.

71
00:08:28,688 --> 00:08:29,848
- Um...
- Here you go.

72
00:08:29,889 --> 00:08:32,517
- Thanks. Mint chocolate chip...
- Mint chocolate chip...

73
00:08:32,559 --> 00:08:34,322
- caramel topping...
- caramel topping...

74
00:08:34,360 --> 00:08:35,884
sprinkles, and whipped cream, please.

75
00:08:35,929 --> 00:08:37,988
Comin' right up.

76
00:08:40,700 --> 00:08:41,826
Thanks.

77
00:08:49,309 --> 00:08:50,503
Hey, guys, wait up.

78
00:08:58,852 --> 00:09:01,844
- I'm spending the night at Jackson's.
- Does Mom know?

79
00:09:01,888 --> 00:09:04,152
- Yeah, she said I could.
- Awesome.

80
00:09:04,190 --> 00:09:06,988
Hey, Jackson, I need you

81
00:09:07,026 --> 00:09:09,790
to take care of my brother tonight...

82
00:09:16,836 --> 00:09:21,500
What are you doing?
Come on, buddy, let's go.

83
00:09:21,541 --> 00:09:23,975
Come on, let's go.

84
00:09:24,010 --> 00:09:25,568
- I'll race you.
- Let's race.

85
00:10:14,360 --> 00:10:15,349
Hey, Camille.

86
00:10:17,864 --> 00:10:18,956
Camille?

87
00:10:21,200 --> 00:10:22,792
Camille?

88
00:10:24,704 --> 00:10:29,539
Hey, Jackson, Philip. Dinner will be
ready in a couple of minutes, okay?

89
00:10:29,575 --> 00:10:31,099
What are we having?

90
00:10:31,144 --> 00:10:33,408
Yeah, it was fun!

91
00:10:52,532 --> 00:10:55,330
Hey, shorty, it's not too loud.

92
00:10:55,368 --> 00:10:58,235
I know.

93
00:10:58,271 --> 00:11:01,206
- You know I like to feel it.
- I know.

94
00:11:03,476 --> 00:11:06,912
- What did she fix?
- I really don't know.

95
00:11:06,946 --> 00:11:10,507
Smells, uh...
creative.

96
00:11:17,290 --> 00:11:18,689
Jackson.

97
00:11:18,725 --> 00:11:20,522
Sorry.

98
00:13:01,260 --> 00:13:03,524
"... one must remember

99
00:13:03,563 --> 00:13:08,000
that men do not physically
live past this life.

100
00:13:08,034 --> 00:13:11,993
In order to protect
the later generations,

101
00:13:12,038 --> 00:13:16,668
man must equip his youth
with the knowledge

102
00:13:16,709 --> 00:13:19,678
from his own experiences,

103
00:13:19,712 --> 00:13:22,237
and to not impose its errors

104
00:13:22,281 --> 00:13:25,648
too rigidly on its youth.

105
00:13:25,685 --> 00:13:30,418
Man must pass on
the aggregated knowledge

106
00:13:30,456 --> 00:13:33,357
to his next generation
with the reminder... "

107
00:13:33,392 --> 00:13:36,293
- Same old same old.
- "... there is much more to learn

108
00:13:36,329 --> 00:13:40,129
than what has been gathered
from his own experiences... "

109
00:13:41,634 --> 00:13:46,435
Have you ever heard the one about the
Two-Legged Alligator Man?

110
00:13:46,472 --> 00:13:50,101
- I don't think so.
- How long have you been in this town?

111
00:13:50,143 --> 00:13:53,670
- It's only the scariest thing ever.
- Tell me.

112
00:13:55,481 --> 00:13:58,848
50 years ago,
there was an old witch.

113
00:13:58,885 --> 00:14:00,716
She lived just
outside of the town,

114
00:14:00,753 --> 00:14:02,914
right next to the water
in an old shack.

115
00:14:02,955 --> 00:14:06,652
She laid eggs, but mostly
she laid eggs for food.

116
00:14:06,692 --> 00:14:10,219
But then one day one of the eggs
rolled off the pile

117
00:14:10,263 --> 00:14:11,730
and into the water.

118
00:14:11,764 --> 00:14:14,528
The witch didn't notice it
until one year later, when

119
00:14:14,567 --> 00:14:18,196
the full-grown Two-Legged Alligator Man
returned and ate her!

120
00:14:24,644 --> 00:14:27,772
Okay, Marty, you've just
eaten a witch now, all right?

121
00:14:27,813 --> 00:14:32,341
But it's not enough, is it?
No, you're still hungry.

122
00:14:32,385 --> 00:14:33,647
Hungry for what?

123
00:14:33,686 --> 00:14:36,621
Linda, show him what he's hungry for!

124
00:14:38,224 --> 00:14:41,819
It's magnificent! Keep it inside,
though. Keep it inside.

125
00:14:41,861 --> 00:14:46,025
- Hey, Marty?
- What?

126
00:14:46,065 --> 00:14:47,862
Over there, on the island!

127
00:14:47,900 --> 00:14:50,027
- Very frightening, isn't it?
- Cripes, it's him!

128
00:14:50,069 --> 00:14:51,832
Are we rolling on this?

129
00:14:53,806 --> 00:14:54,830
Is it true?

130
00:14:54,874 --> 00:15:00,210
Yes, I believe he's
out there somewhere.

131
00:15:00,246 --> 00:15:04,774
Maybe in some way he's
protecting our shore,

132
00:15:04,817 --> 00:15:08,617
dedicated to the fine people
of this town.

133
00:15:08,654 --> 00:15:11,316
I believe it.

134
00:15:11,357 --> 00:15:13,291
Maybe that makes it real.

135
00:15:13,326 --> 00:15:15,055
Total poppycock.

136
00:15:15,094 --> 00:15:18,427
Is that a band? I think I...
yeah, I heard of them. A band.

137
00:15:18,464 --> 00:15:20,159
Everybody else thinks so.

138
00:15:20,199 --> 00:15:22,667
Some people say he
roams the streets late at night,

139
00:15:22,702 --> 00:15:23,691
looking for...

140
00:15:25,705 --> 00:15:27,832
What was that?

141
00:15:27,873 --> 00:15:31,468
looking for food...
going from house to house

142
00:15:31,510 --> 00:15:34,343
looking for kids
who sneak out at night.

143
00:15:34,380 --> 00:15:36,712
- Like us.
- Like us.

144
00:15:43,222 --> 00:15:45,622
I told you he was taking
picture earlier.

145
00:15:45,658 --> 00:15:47,319
He's weird.

146
00:15:47,360 --> 00:15:49,658
- Yeah. Let's follow him.
- Okay.

147
00:16:40,613 --> 00:16:43,878
Seems like I'm the center of attention
even in the middle of the night.

148
00:16:43,916 --> 00:16:45,816
- We didn't mean to.
- Yeah, we didn't know

149
00:16:45,851 --> 00:16:48,843
- you were out here taking pictures.
- You didn't know?

150
00:16:49,922 --> 00:16:51,719
What are you doing?

151
00:16:51,757 --> 00:16:55,716
I'm taking pictures for visual
reference. I'm building a model.

152
00:16:55,761 --> 00:16:59,993
- I heard about that.
- Did you hear about it?

153
00:17:00,032 --> 00:17:02,125
You know, they make
smaller cameras than that.

154
00:17:02,168 --> 00:17:04,830
Yeah, they do. I know.

155
00:17:04,870 --> 00:17:06,667
It's just that I like to
do my own development.

156
00:17:06,706 --> 00:17:10,107
I see it sort of
as a process, you know?

157
00:17:10,142 --> 00:17:14,442
This old thing
just feels good in my hands.

158
00:17:16,382 --> 00:17:17,371
Want to try it?

159
00:17:25,624 --> 00:17:28,388
- Look at this.
- How would you boys

160
00:17:28,427 --> 00:17:30,554
- like to do me a favor?
- What?

161
00:17:30,596 --> 00:17:34,225
Well, the people in this town

162
00:17:34,266 --> 00:17:36,666
must think I'm pretty strange.
They keep looking at me

163
00:17:36,702 --> 00:17:38,863
like I got three eyes,

164
00:17:38,904 --> 00:17:41,600
Which I don't.

165
00:17:43,376 --> 00:17:46,607
You know, I think somebody

166
00:17:46,645 --> 00:17:48,579
who was good at sneaking around

167
00:17:48,614 --> 00:17:51,082
could probably take
a lot better pictures than me.

168
00:17:51,117 --> 00:17:55,349
I need pictures of details,
details.

169
00:17:55,388 --> 00:17:58,357
You know about details, right?
Details?

170
00:17:58,391 --> 00:18:01,258
- Details, like...
- Yeah.

171
00:18:01,293 --> 00:18:06,026
This model that I am gonna make
is gonna be the spitting image.

172
00:18:07,733 --> 00:18:12,830
And what I would do is
I would make sure that you

173
00:18:12,872 --> 00:18:15,102
- had film whenever you wanted it.
- Okay.

174
00:18:15,141 --> 00:18:17,632
I just want you to
keep taking pictures...

175
00:18:17,676 --> 00:18:22,136
people, places, and things.

176
00:18:22,181 --> 00:18:24,741
- Okay.
- Think you can figure out how it works?

177
00:18:24,784 --> 00:18:25,773
Let me show you something.

178
00:18:25,818 --> 00:18:29,254
Let me show you how it works.

179
00:18:30,790 --> 00:18:33,122
Jeez, Phil, careful.
You almost dropped it.

180
00:18:33,159 --> 00:18:36,219
Here, take it.

181
00:18:36,262 --> 00:18:39,425
It's heavy.

182
00:18:39,465 --> 00:18:41,524
What should we
take pictures of tomorrow?

183
00:18:41,567 --> 00:18:45,936
I don't know. Everything.

184
00:18:48,140 --> 00:18:50,131
It was our first spadeful of dirt

185
00:18:50,176 --> 00:18:53,304
in a summer of searching
for buried treasure.

186
00:18:53,345 --> 00:18:56,837
Eli had us wide-eyed, you know?

187
00:18:56,882 --> 00:18:58,941
And when you first have
a camera in your hands,

188
00:18:58,984 --> 00:19:02,317
everything in the world looks
as though it should be photographed.

189
00:20:56,201 --> 00:20:59,602
- Gotta get home to Dad.
- We got one picture left.

190
00:20:59,638 --> 00:21:01,299
Save it. I'll see you
tomorrow morning.

191
00:21:01,340 --> 00:21:02,830
Okay. Later.

192
00:21:02,875 --> 00:21:04,502
Bye, Philip!

193
00:21:09,315 --> 00:21:11,875
- Hey, Mom.
- Hey, you.

194
00:21:14,587 --> 00:21:16,987
We got this great camera
from Eli Cottonmouth.

195
00:21:17,022 --> 00:21:20,423
The stranger?
That model guy? He's weird.

196
00:21:20,459 --> 00:21:21,483
Yeah.

197
00:21:22,861 --> 00:21:25,295
We got one picture left.

198
00:21:27,266 --> 00:21:29,632
Okay...

199
00:21:29,668 --> 00:21:31,329
Turn around.

200
00:21:32,905 --> 00:21:33,894
Smile.

201
00:21:45,484 --> 00:21:48,009
Come on. It's time to go inside.

202
00:22:03,636 --> 00:22:05,126
That's my house.

203
00:22:07,973 --> 00:22:09,838
Oh, yeah.

204
00:22:21,320 --> 00:22:23,550
One day you boys are gonna
know what it's like to die.

205
00:22:23,589 --> 00:22:25,523
It is certain.
Don't forget that.

206
00:22:34,199 --> 00:22:38,135
Do you think he was saying
he's going to kill us

207
00:22:38,170 --> 00:22:39,762
if we don't take better pictures?

208
00:22:39,805 --> 00:22:41,102
I really don't.

209
00:22:41,140 --> 00:22:43,301
Okay.

210
00:22:43,342 --> 00:22:46,402
Man...

211
00:22:46,445 --> 00:22:48,310
Death.

212
00:22:48,347 --> 00:22:50,315
Yeah.

213
00:22:50,349 --> 00:22:52,317
I mean, do you think it'll hurt?

214
00:22:52,351 --> 00:22:54,842
I guess that depends.

215
00:22:54,887 --> 00:22:57,378
Fire. Burning I think would suck.

216
00:22:57,423 --> 00:22:58,981
It's the smoke that gets you.

217
00:22:59,024 --> 00:23:01,822
- Shut up. It's the fire.
- No, I saw this thing on TV.

218
00:23:01,860 --> 00:23:03,919
Drowning.

219
00:23:03,962 --> 00:23:06,089
Man, one time I had this dream...

220
00:23:06,131 --> 00:23:07,826
Yeah, you told me.

221
00:23:07,866 --> 00:23:10,164
Brain cancer.

222
00:23:10,202 --> 00:23:11,794
- My aunt...
- Then what?

223
00:23:11,837 --> 00:23:12,826
What do you mean?

224
00:23:12,871 --> 00:23:15,203
What happens next...

225
00:23:15,240 --> 00:23:18,038
the second after?

226
00:23:18,077 --> 00:23:20,409
What happens?

227
00:23:27,820 --> 00:23:30,380
You boys sure are quiet.

228
00:23:30,422 --> 00:23:33,050
Got some pie in the fridge.

229
00:23:33,092 --> 00:23:34,116
No.

230
00:23:34,159 --> 00:23:37,754
I don't think we're hungry,
thanks.

231
00:23:40,165 --> 00:23:41,723
We should get your dad a dog.

232
00:23:41,767 --> 00:23:43,826
I don't think he likes animals.

233
00:23:43,869 --> 00:23:46,463
A chihuahua puppy's for sale.

234
00:23:46,505 --> 00:23:48,735
Chihuahuas are gross.

235
00:23:48,774 --> 00:23:51,368
What are you reading?

236
00:23:51,410 --> 00:23:53,901
Classifieds.

237
00:23:53,946 --> 00:23:55,277
Here's my favorite:

238
00:23:55,314 --> 00:23:58,078
The Personals.

239
00:23:58,117 --> 00:24:01,814
"SWF seeking disappointment.

240
00:24:01,854 --> 00:24:03,981
Prove me wrong. "

241
00:24:04,022 --> 00:24:06,217
Wow!

242
00:24:07,793 --> 00:24:09,522
Okay, this one's good.

243
00:24:09,561 --> 00:24:11,756
"Unrepentant clog-wearer

244
00:24:11,797 --> 00:24:14,061
- seeking same. "
- What's a clog?

245
00:24:14,099 --> 00:24:16,863
This one sounds like a five-year-old.

246
00:24:16,902 --> 00:24:21,635
"Sitting alone on my swing set
seeking a push. "

247
00:24:21,673 --> 00:24:24,267
Yeah, I'm not sure that's legal.

248
00:24:38,157 --> 00:24:39,249
Philip.

249
00:24:47,132 --> 00:24:50,124
I don't know why it bothered me so much.

250
00:24:50,169 --> 00:24:52,694
I guess I always knew deep down

251
00:24:52,738 --> 00:24:55,104
that my father liked to fool around.

252
00:24:55,140 --> 00:24:59,839
But my mom,
she was a rock in my mind.

253
00:24:59,878 --> 00:25:01,903
It never occurred to me

254
00:25:01,947 --> 00:25:05,007
that she would want to be with
a man who wasn't my dad.

255
00:25:17,296 --> 00:25:19,161
Need a push?

256
00:25:21,700 --> 00:25:23,258
Hi.

257
